prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: As we are interested in the continuum of these sources, we request a factor of 16 spectral averaging to reduce data rates and volumes. However, the resulting ~9 km/s resolution will ensure these data can be used to search for serendipitous spectral line sources in the field of view.
We seek integrated ISM mass measurements for our sources. At redshifts z~3, our 1" requested resolution spans 7.5kpc. Thus, we expect most of our sources to be unresolved.

The requested RMS will enable us to detect ISM masses of ~3e10 M_sun at 5sigma across the range of redshifts of our targets. This will enable us to place meaningful constraints on the ISM mass of our matched control sample for z>3 AGN.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Measuring the gas and dust contents in galaxies is critical for our understanding of galaxy evolution, as this is the fuel for both star formation and supermassive black hole (SMBH) growth. Until recently, these measurements have been done using the CO lines. However, it is far more efficient to derive the total mass in the interstellar medium (ISM) using a single measurement of the far-IR flux in the optically thin Rayleigh-Jeans. This, combined with the unsurpassed sensitivity of ALMA and the so-called "negative k-correction", allows for the first time to measure ISM masses for sizable samples of galaxies up to high redshifts. Here, we propose to obtain ALMA band 6 measurements of the dust continuum fluxes for a sample of 27 host galaxies of Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN) at z>3 in the COSMOS field and a control sample of inactive galaxies matched in both stellar mass and redshift. With these data we will derive ISM masses as a function of stellar mass and other physical properties, and test if AGN host galaxies at high redshifts are richer in gas in comparison to normal galaxies and hence shed light on the mechanism triggering SMBH growth episodes and its evolution.
